Contact tracing is the systematic identification and monitoring of all persons who might have been exposed to a person diagnosed with an infectious disease. Because these persons are at risk of developing disease, contacts should self- monitor and may be monitored by the local health department for 14 days (the maximum incubation period) from the last date they had exposure to a confirmed case.

The goals of contact tracing are to: 1. Rapidly identify all potential contacts, 2. Ensure appropriate medical evaluation and care if the contact becomes symptomatic, and 3. Ensure immediate isolation precautions are implemented if the contact becomes symptomatic.
